<p class="p">The “absolute threshold shift” method first defines the present-day threshold temperature in absolute terms (
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M3" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) and then increases it in the future. Assessments have assumed shifts of the ERF in the future by up to 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M4" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">2</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (
 <xref rid="c29" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Jenkins et al. 2014</xref>), 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M5" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">2.4</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (
 <xref rid="c28" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Huynen and Martens 2015</xref>), 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M6" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">3</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (
 <xref rid="c11" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Dessai 2003</xref>) and 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M7" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">4</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (
 <xref rid="c14" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Gosling et al. 2009</xref>). This is perhaps the most straightforward method, which is why it has been used most frequently in previous studies. The magnitude of the shift tends to be selected arbitrarily and to be justified with no reference to empirical evidence from epidemiological studies.
</p>
